Date:  0/3/1770
Source:  Journal
Author:  BANKS
Vol / Page:  2/27
Edition:  1962
Quote:  [Patoo patoos] generally made of Bone ... or of coarse black Jasper very hard.  -->[fn3] ... [Banks] uses the term `Jasper' rather loosely; he may be here referring to the baked argyllite much used in the Marlborough Sounds area which he would certainly have seen at Queen X Charlotte Sound. Best (II p. 259) thinks it was a kind of greywacke. 2. =? greenstone.
Notes:

Date:  4/6/1773
Source:  Journal
Author:  BAYLY
Vol / Page:
Edition:  1962
Quote:  The Indians are fond of green stone they have among them which they call Poanamo. It is a kind of Jasper. With this they make their Togie, or ads of & chissles to carve with, & bobs for their years [ears] & gorgets to hang at the breast.
Notes:  1773 June 4 Bayly's Journal in 1908 McNab Historical Records 2/209

Date:  25/2/1777
Source:  Cook's Journals
Author:  ANDERSON
Vol / Page:  2/27
Edition:  1962
Quote:  Neither is there any mineral worth notice but a green jasper or serpent stone of which the natives make their tools and ornaments.
